╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: ls                                           ║
║  Classification: Core Tool                                    ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Created by Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie in 1971 for Unix  │
│  on the PDP-7. The name is simply short for "list." In the    │
│  early days, every keystroke mattered - terminals were slow,  │
│  and memory was measured in kilobytes. Two-letter commands    │
│  like ls, cd, rm, and cp saved precious time and resources.   │
│  The command has grown from 5 options in 1972 to over 60      │
│  today, yet the basics remain unchanged.                      │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Think of ls as asking a directory "What's inside you?"       │
│                                                                │
│      ┌─────────────────────┐                                   │
│      │   Directory (.)     │                                   │
│      │  ┌────┬────┬────┐   │                                   │
│      │  │file│file│dir/│   │  ← ls sees this                  │
│      │  └────┴────┴────┘   │                                   │
│      └─────────────────────┘                                   │
│                                                                │
│  Key flags change what you see:                                │
│                                                                │
│    ls       → names only                                       │
│    ls -l    → long format (permissions, size, date)           │
│    ls -a    → all files (including hidden .dotfiles)          │
│    ls -la   → both: all files in long format                  │
│                                                                │
│  The dot prefix convention: files starting with . are hidden  │
│  by default. This was actually a bug that became a feature!   │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Works well with: cd, pwd, find, tree                       │
│  • Alternatives: find (for searching), tree (for structure)   │
│  • Builds toward: Understanding file permissions, navigation  │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "When troubleshooting, always start with 'ls -la'. The -a    │
│  reveals hidden configuration files that are often the source │
│  of mysterious behavior. Many ship systems store their state  │
│  in .dotfiles - invisible unless you ask to see them."        │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
